<lb corresp="#b1"/><gap reason="lost"/><w>k<supplied>e</supplied>rek<supplied>au</supplied>n<supplied>a</supplied></w><w>k<gap reason="plain" unit="part"/></w><gap reason="lost"/>
<lb corresp="#b2"/><gap reason="lost"/><w><supplied>sa</supplied>nti</w><w>kopāḥ</w><w>kete</w><gap reason="plain" quantity="1"/><gap reason="lost"/>
<lb corresp="#b3"/><gap reason="lost"/><w><supplied>skwass</supplied>o<supplied>nt</supplied></w><w>ṣek</w><w>snai</w><w>me<supplied>nts</supplied>i</w><gap reason="lost"/></p>
         </div>
         <div type="comments">
            <p><note type="remarks">The faint text that appears on both the recto and the verso shines through from the other side; it is not an imprint from another fragment.</note><note corresp="#a1" type="philcomment">: cf. Uv30.28b.</note><note corresp="#a2" type="philcomment">: cf. Uv30.29b. The preceding <hi>nt·</hi> can hardly be a rendering of <hi>chitvā</hi> of Uv30.29a <hi>sarvā hy āśāstayaś chitvā</hi>. Possibly it is the final of the translation of <hi>āśāstayas</hi> 'desires'.</note><note corresp="#a3" type="philcomment">: cf. Uv30.30a.</note><note corresp="#a4" type="philcomment">: cf. Uv30.30d.</note><note corresp="#b1" type="philcomment">: cf. Uv30.36b <hi>kāmapaṅkaughatāriṇām</hi>. <hi>kerek(au)n(a)</hi> renders <hi>°ogha°</hi>; <hi>kätkaucañ</hi> or a similar form renders <hi>°tāriṇām</hi>.</note><note corresp="#b2" type="philcomment">: cf. Uv30.37a.</note><note corresp="#b3" type="philcomment">: cf. Uv30.37c <hi>akhilaṃ taṃ sukhinaṃ sadā viśokaṃ</hi>.</note></p>
         </div>
